article.description:
Wisconsin pulled within a half-game of
first place in the Big Ten with a 64-53 victory over Michigan State
on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Wisconsin closes in on Purdue and Michigan with win
article.linkText: Wisconsin wins 13th straight Big Ten home game
article.story:
MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin pulled within a half-game of first place in the Big Ten with a 64-53 victory over Michigan State on Tuesday night.

	   Kirk Penney, Devin Harris and Mike Wilkinson led the Badgers
with 14 points apiece as the Badgers improved to 17-5 (7-3 Big
Ten). They trail Purdue and Michigan by half a game, while Michigan
State (13-9, 5-5 Big Ten) had its three-game winning streak
snapped.

	   Wisconsin kept intact its perfect home conference record in the
Bo Ryan era, winning its 13th consecutive Big Ten home game. The
Badgers have won 22 of their last 23 conference home games.

	   Freshman Erazem Lorbek led the Spartans with a dominant
second-half performance. All 19 of Lorbek's points came in the
second half after playing just nine minutes and attempting one shot before the break.

	   With 6-foot-11 center Paul Davis and 6-8 forward Aloysius
Anagonye sidelined early in the second half with three fouls each,
Lorbek picked up the slack for the Spartans inside. He rattled off
eight consecutive points in less than two minutes, pulling MSU
within 41-37 with 12:28 remaining in the game.

	   Four minutes later, Lorbek converted a three-point play inside
on a pinpoint bounce pass from Kelvin Torbert to pull the Spartans
within 46-44.

	   Torbert hit a shot to tie the game 48-48 with 5:25 remaining,
but Wisconsin used four consecutive points by Penney and a clutch
3-pointer by Alando Tucker to spark a 16-5 run to close out the victory.

	   Tucker put an exclamation point on the win at the buzzer,
slamming home an alley-oop pass by Harris to send the crowd home
buzzing. Wisconsin only turned the ball over twice in the first
half, but struggled to build a substantial early lead because of
its poor shooting.

	   The Badgers hit just five of their first 21 field goals, and
finished the half at 31.3 percent shooting.

	   An early 6 p.m. start and a nasty snowstorm that swept in just
before rush hour left the Kohl Center less than half-full when the
nationally televised game tipped off. Although the matchup was
technically a sellout, there were patches of empty seats until
midway through the second half.

	   In a half that saw the lead change hands seven times, the
Badgers pulled to a 31-27 advantage at the break behind the hot
hand of Wilkinson. After missing six of his first seven attempts,
Wilkinson hit three of his next four shots and made two free throws
for 12 points in the first half.

	   The Spartans were hurt by two quick fouls to Anagonye, who sat
for the final 8:30 of the half. In the five minutes that Anagonye
was on the floor, Michigan State outscored Wisconsin 8-2.
